{"headings":["introduction","repetition-within-retrieved-context-theory","episode-specific-reinstatement-within-a-retrieved-context-framework","roadmap","instance-cmr-an-episode-specific-retrieved-context-account-of-memory-search","representations-and-memory-architecture","study-dynamics","recall-dynamics","task-implementations-and-termination","variants-and-extensions","methodological-framework","defining-and-measuring-repetition-effects","datasets","model-evaluation","model-validation-on-non-repetition-lists","reassessing-empirical-benchmarks-against-cmr","the-spacing-effect","diagnostic-tests-of-cross-occurrence-associative-interference","analytic-definitions","repetition-lag-crp-outgoing","repetition-lag-crp-incoming-backward-variant","cross-occurrence-neighbor-contiguity-free-recall","serial-forward-chaining-test-serial-recall","cross-occurrence-neighbor-transitions","the-repetition-lag-crp","backwardincoming-variant-of-the-repetition-lag-crp","forward-chaining-in-serial-recall","summary-noninterference-across-tasks","ablation-analysis-cmr-without-study-phase-retrieval","instance-cmr-eliminating-associative-interference-at-encoding-and-retrieval","exploring-reinforcement-without-associative-blending-at-study","formal-comparison-across-datasets","general-discussion","references"],"entries":[{"key":"fig-cmr_nospr_benchmarks","order":{"number":11,"section":[8,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"CMR-NoSPR benchmarks (free recall). Simulated serial-position curves (SPC; top left), lag-CRP (top right), and probability of first/next recall (bottom) for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved, scored with the symmetric baseline. Eliminating study-phase reinstatement leaves benchmark fits intact."},{"key":"eq-6","order":{"number":6,"section":[2,2,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-rep-crp-schematic","parent":"fig-rep-crp-base","caption":"","order":{"number":1}},{"key":"eq-8","order":{"number":8,"section":[2,3,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-healey2014memory","order":{"number":2,"section":[5,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Summary statistic fits to @healey2014memory. Left: standard CMR. Right: Instance-CMR. Top: lag-CRP. Middle: probability of first recall. Bottom: serial position curve."},{"key":"fig-os_serial_rep_crp","order":{"number":19,"section":[9,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Cross-occurrence forward errors in serial recall (data vs Instance-CMR). Left: @logan2021serial. Right: @kahana2000interresponse. Top row (data): For items studied at positions i and j, each panel plots the conditional probability— after correct report through the first occurrence at position i – of an erroneous transition to the second occurrence’s forward neighbors (i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}1 and i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}2), contrasting mixed lists with their position-matched, symmetric baseline. Bottom row (CMR-OS): Occurrence-Specific CMR simulations fitted separately to each dataset and scored with the identical baseline procedure."},{"key":"fig-icmr_os_spacing","order":{"number":16,"section":[9,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Instance-CMR spacing function. Simulated spacing curves for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved. The spacing advantage is preserved without blending at test; the model does not reproduce the apparent steeper slope for mixed lists in the data (cf. @fig-spacing)."},{"key":"eq-4","order":{"number":4,"section":[2,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-reinf_rep_lag_crp","order":{"number":23,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Repetition lag-CRP (outgoing): data vs ICMR-Reinf. Top: mixed lists (left) and matched-control baseline (right) from @lohnas2014retrieved. Bottom: ICMR-Reinf simulations scored identically. In mixed lists, the +1 bin and nearby lags show a larger first-over-second separation than in baseline—matching the data’s boosted separation. Balanced-access (blending) is absent."},{"key":"fig-spacing","order":{"number":5,"section":[6,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"The spacing effect for mixed vs control list trials from @lohnas2014retrieved. Left: data, right: simulations of standard CMR fitted to the data."},{"key":"fig-os_neighbor_contiguity","order":{"number":17,"section":[9,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Instance-CMR: cross-occurrence neighbor transitions (centered lag-CRPs). Left: triggers from forward neighbors of the first presentation (i{+}1,i{+}2), lags centered on the second (\\ell=\\text{next}-j). Right: symmetric variant (triggers j{+}1,j{+}2; lags centered on i). Mixed–minus–baseline curves sit at baseline in both directions, consistent with no knitting across neighborhoods."},{"key":"fig-nospr_neighbor_contiguity","order":{"number":13,"section":[8,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"CMR-NoSPR: cross-occurrence neighbor transitions (centered lag-CRPs). Left: triggers from forward neighbors of the first presentation and lags centered on the second. Right: triggers from forward neighbors of the second and lags centered on the first. Curves plot mixed–minus–matched-control probabilities with symmetric scoring. With distinctive encoding contexts, cross-occurrence neighbor bins lie at baseline in both directions—neighbor knitting is abolished."},{"key":"tbl-aic-os-vs-cmr","order":{"number":4,"section":[10,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Pairwise AIC weights (Instance-CMR vs Standard CMR). OS is preferred in every dataset."},{"key":"eq-11","order":{"number":11,"section":[2,4,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"eq-3","order":{"number":3,"section":[2,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"tbl-fit-sr","order":{"number":3,"section":[10,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Serial‑recall model fits (−log L; lower is better). ICMR‑NoSPR was not evaluated for the serial‑recall datasets. Values are participant means ± bootstrapped 95% CIs (subjects)."},{"key":"eq-2","order":{"number":2,"section":[2,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-os_rep_lag_crp","order":{"number":18,"section":[9,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Repetition lag-CRP (outgoing): data vs Instance-CMR. Top row: mixed lists (left) and matched-control baseline (right) from @lohnas2014retrieved. Bottom row: Instance-CMR simulations scored identically. First- vs second-centered curves remain separated (no blending). Unlike the data (top-left), the mixed-minus-baseline separation is not substantially enlarged in Instance-CMR, fixing interference but not the boosted first-over-second advantage."},{"key":"fig-cmr_benchmarks","order":{"number":4,"section":[6,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Standard CMR predictions for mixed and control list trials from trials from @lohnas2014retrieved, with symmetric scoring over matched serial positions of repeated items. Left: recall rate by serial position (serial position curve, SPC). Middle: conditional response probability (CRP) by lag. Right: probability of first recall by serial position."},{"key":"eq-5","order":{"number":5,"section":[2,2,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-icmr-schematic","order":{"number":1,"section":[1,2,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"A schematic comparing standard CMR and our proposed episode-specific reformulation Instance-CMR in lists with item repetitions."},{"key":"fig-icmr_reinf_spacing","order":{"number":21,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"ICMR-Reinf spacing function. Simulated spacing curves for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved. The spacing advantage is preserved; the model does not, by itself, produce the additional steepening seen in mixed lists (cf. @fig-spacing)."},{"key":"fig-reinf_neighbor_contiguity","order":{"number":22,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"ICMR-Reinf: cross-occurrence neighbor transitions (centered lag-CRPs). Left: triggers from forward neighbors of the first presentation (i{+}1,i{+}2), lags centered on the second (\\ell=text{next}-j). Right: symmetric variant (triggers j{+}1,j{+}2; lags centered on i). Mixed–minus–baseline curves remain flat at the other occurrence’s neighbors (no knitting). A selective lag = 0 elevation emerges in the first→second variant, consistent with boosted access to the repeated item itself."},{"key":"tbl-aic-fr","order":{"number":5,"section":[10,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Three-way AIC weights in free recall. After penalization, ICMR-Reinf is preferred; OS is second; Standard CMR is not competitive."},{"key":"fig-icmr_os_benchmarks","order":{"number":15,"section":[9,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Instance-CMR benchmarks (free recall). Simulated serial-position curves (SPC; top left), lag-CRP (top right), and probability of first/next recall (bottom) for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved under symmetric scoring. Occurrence-specific reinstatement at test preserves benchmark fits."},{"key":"fig-reinf_serial_rep_crp","order":{"number":25,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Cross-occurrence forward errors in serial recall (data vs ICMR-Reinf; @logan2021serial; @kahana2000interresponse). Top: data; bottom: ICMR-Reinf simulations. Panels plot, for items studied at i and j, the conditional probability—after correct report through i—of erroneous transitions to the second occurrence’s forward neighbors (i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}1 and i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}2), contrasted with matched pseudo-repeater baselines. ICMR-Reinf reproduces the data’s non-elevation."},{"key":"fig-reinf_back_rep_crp","order":{"number":24,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Repetition lag-CRP (incoming/backward). Top: mixed lists (left) and matched-control baseline (right) from @lohnas2014retrieved. Bottom: ICMR-Reinf simulations scored identically. In mixed lists, the +1 bin and nearby lags show a larger first-over-second separation than in baseline—matching the data’s boosted separation. Balanced-access (blending) is absent."},{"key":"tbl-fit-fr","order":{"number":2,"section":[10,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Free‑recall model fits (−log L; lower is better). Values are participant means ± bootstrapped 95% CIs (subjects)."},{"key":"fig-neighbor_contiguity","order":{"number":7,"section":[7,2,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Cross-occurrence neighbor transitions as centered lag-CRPs (free recall). Top row (data), bottom row (CMR simulations). Left column (first→second): triggers are forward neighbors of the first presentation (i{+}1,i{+}2); lags are centered on the second presentation at j (so \\ell=\\text{next}-j). Right column (second→first): triggers are forward neighbors of the second presentation (j{+}1,j{+}2); lags are centered on the first presentation at i (so \\ell=\\text{next}-i). All curves plot mixed–minus–matched-control probabilities using the symmetric baseline. In the data, cross-occurrence neighbor bins (e.g., \\ell=\\pm1,\\pm2) sit near baseline in both directions, with a selective elevation at \\ell=0 (the repeater itself) only in the first→second case. Standard CMR predicts pronounced above-baseline peaks at the other occurrence’s neighbors in both directions, consistent with associative blending."},{"key":"fig-icmr_reinf_benchmarks","order":{"number":20,"section":[10,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"ICMR-Reinf benchmarks (free recall). Simulated serial-position curves (SPC; top left), lag-CRP (top right), and probability of first/next recall (bottom) for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved under symmetric scoring. Reinforcement at study preserves benchmark fits."},{"key":"fig-control_method","order":{"number":3,"section":[6,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Raw (Left) vs control-corrected (Right) benchmark summary statistics for mixed vs control list trials from @lohnas2014retrieved. Top row: recall rate by serial position (serial position curve, SPC). Second row: conditional response probability (CRP) by lag. Third row: probability of first recall by serial position."},{"key":"eq-7","order":{"number":7,"section":[2,3,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-serial_rep_crp","order":{"number":10,"section":[7,5,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Cross-occurrence forward errors in serial recall (two datasets). Left: @logan2021serial. Right: @kahana2000interresponse. Top row (data): For items studied at positions i and j, each panel plots the conditional probability— after correct report through the first occurrence at position i – of an erroneous transition to the second occurrence’s forward neighbors (i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}1 and i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}2), contrasting mixed lists with their position-matched, symmetric baseline. Bottom row (CMR): standard CMR simulations fitted separately to each dataset and scored with the identical baseline procedure. In both datasets, data show no elevation of i\\!\\rightarrow\\!j{+}1/j{+}2 errors relative to baseline (non-interference), whereas CMR predicts a clear error elevation (associative interference)."},{"key":"fig-backward_rep_lag_crp","order":{"number":9,"section":[7,4,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Repetition lag-CRP (incoming/backward): data vs CMR. Top row (data): mixed lists (left) and baseline (right) for transitions to repeated items. Bottom row (CMR): simulations. In data, transitions to repeated items are more frequently from the backward neighbor of the item’s first presentation than from the second, especially in mixed lists but also in the position-matched baseline. By contrast, CMR predicts a weaker first-over-second advantage for incoming transitions."},{"key":"fig-nospr_rep_lag_crp","order":{"number":14,"section":[8,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"CMR-NoSPR: repetition lag-CRP (outgoing). Mixed lists (left) and matched-control baseline (right) from simulations. First- vs second-centered curves are more balanced than in baseline, consistent with lingering cross-occurrence blending at retrieval."},{"key":"fig-repetition_lag_crp","order":{"number":8,"section":[7,3,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Repetition lag-CRP (outgoing): data vs CMR. Top row (data): mixed lists (left) and matched-control baseline (right), each showing two centered curves (first-centered vs second-centered). Bottom row (CMR): same for simulations. In data, separation (e.g., +1 bin) favors the first-occurrence neighborhood and is larger than in baseline; CMR predicts reduced separation (balanced access), consistent with blending."},{"key":"fig-rep-crp-base","order":{"number":6,"section":[7,1,1,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"The repetition lag-CRP. A. The lag-contiguity effect conceptualizes free-recall search as movement along a mental timeline, but repeated items occupy two positions on that timeline. B. Extending the lag-CRP, we tabulate transitions from a recalled repeater relative to both its study positions. Illustration from mixed lists in @lohnas2014retrieved."},{"key":"tbl-cmr-parameters","order":{"number":1,"section":[2,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"Parameters and structures specifying Instance-CMR."},{"key":"eq-1","order":{"number":1,"section":[2,1,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"fig-nospr_spacing","order":{"number":12,"section":[8,0,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":"CMR-NoSPR spacing function. Simulated spacing curves for mixed vs matched-control lists from @lohnas2014retrieved. The spacing advantage is preserved without study-phase reinstatement."},{"key":"eq-10","order":{"number":10,"section":[2,3,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""},{"key":"eq-9","order":{"number":9,"section":[2,3,0,0,0,0,0]},"caption":""}]}